<title type="html"><![CDATA[Unskippable cut scenes]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6471&amp;p=62526#p62526"><![CDATA[
Well, well just wanted to point something :<br />I don't know how many of you know about the GBA Mega Man Battle Network series, it's basically RPG Mega Man games. There is 6 of them, and it's pretty obvious the game engine has been completely revised between 3 and 4 (I'm talking about overworld game engine, not battles which are similar in all 6 games). This makes 1-3 use game engine A, and 4-6 uses game engine B.<br /><br />1-3 have skippable cut-scenes, and 4-6 have non-skippable cut-scenes.<br />Because the story of the games is kind of significant, you'd want to watch the scene at least once. However, like in the NES Mega Man games, the bosses needs quite some strategy to be beaten and it's very unlikely you'll success on your first try. This is why it's really annoying to have non-skippable cutscenes in 4-6 : You're forced to watch the scenes before the boss again and again.<br /><br />HOWEVER, I found myself skipping important scenes in MMBN1-3 by pressing a button by accident, which to be honest just as annoying. I'm not saying cut-scenes should be unskippable, but they shouldn't be too easily skippable. The best is : Player press "start", then the game go to a screen where it brings a menu like "skip - resmue - rewind". That way everyone is happy. Rare are games who actually does this tough, Final Fantasy 12 is one of them, but the story line of this game is in my opinion pure crap (very unlike all it's predecessor) so well... at least you can skip the crap.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />I will say, however, that everyone I know IRL cares very little for in game cutscenes and just want to play the game. I think only the hardcore gamer nerds (no offense) really care, and these days that makes up a rather small percentage of all gamers.<br /></div><br />You aren't the great majority of gamers, nor am I or anyone else here. If you include all granddads who play Wii sport, Nintendogs and all this crap in the majority of gamers, then you're probably right. However, I wouldn't consider them gamers.<br />You'd be surprised that many casual gamers actually play RPGs almost only for their story and the easier the game is, the better for them. I have my sis in mind here (okay she's not the majority of gamers either), and to be honnest I don't quite understand what is the point of playing if you don't care about the gameplay.<br /><br />However, it's not because most of you play NES games all day, and that NES games never have any cutscenes (exept Ninja Gaiden) that cutscenes are bad. They aren't necessary for a good game (we all know SMB, etc...), but honnestly a good story and good/fun scenes really makes a game very supperior to the average (see the FF series).<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=38">Bregalad</a> — Sun Jun 06, 2010 12:02 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
