<title type="html"><![CDATA[Unskippable cut scenes]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6471&amp;p=62484#p62484"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">UncleSporky wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />I have the same lack of remorse for players who don't read the manual and get upset when they don't know how to jump, or who skip the "boring tutorial" and get upset when they don't know how to equip an item...or those who don't watch a scene that gives them vital information.<br /></div><br /><br />Addressed in a previous post.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />In short, the player has responsibility to absorb the information I give him if he wants to enjoy my game. I'm not a bad designer if he refuses my help.<br /></div><br /><br />You're a bad designer for insisting upon a way to help that people are likely to refuse.  A better designer would do a better job of helping.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />And watching scenes is the primary reason some people play video games.  Everyone has their own tastes, and it's up to the consumer to buy games that match theirs.<br /></div><br /><br />But why intentionally alienate people by forcing them watch cutscenes when you can just as easily present the same information in a more interesting / easier to absorb way?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />And if you don't like watching cutscenes then you shouldn't buy a cinematic, story-heavy game.<br /></div><br /><br />The thing is these games <em>don't need to be</em> cinematic.  I love the gameplay in Cave Story.  It's tons of fun.<br /><br />The problem with it is that the cutscenes are not skippable.  I've seen them all several times.  I can't play the game anymore because I find it tiresome to repeatedly tap the action button and wait for those scenes to end.  It's a <em>serious</em> replay killer, and a <em>serious</em> flaw in the game.<br /><br />There is absolutely no reason those cutscenes shouldn't have been skippable.  It was a terrible design decision to make them nonskippable.<br /><br />Same is true of every game.  That was my original claim, and my original point.  I stand by that.<br /><br />If you like the cutscenes, watch them.  If you don't, it costs <em>absolutly nothing</em> to let the player skip them.  So let them skip them if they choose.  If it means more people will enjoy the game, it's a good thing.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />No game developer attempts to make a game that absolutely everyone will enjoy<br /></div><br /><br />Of course.  I said as much in an earlier post.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Konami makes long, drawn out, highly complicated cutscenes in Metal Gear because they know their target audience wants that.<br /></div><br /><br />And they'd be wrong if they didn't make their cut scenes skippable.<br /><br />All the people that like Metal Gear would still like it.  But those people that find cutscenes boring would also like it more.  Everyone wins when they're skippable.  There's no reason not to put it in every game.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=33">Disch</a> — Sat Jun 05, 2010 8:13 pm</p><hr />
