<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6471&amp;p=62471#p62471"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />I think you nailed it. Perhaps you can have your 2 minute cutscene, but break it up into three parts: the first minute and a half (FFing allowed), the 10 seconds that are important (no FFing unless this specific cutscene has been shown since power-on), and then the 20 second transition into gameplay (FFing allowed).<br /></div><br /><br />I guess that would be an improvement, but it seems like roundabout way to make a poor design more tolerable.<br /><br />It's better if you just don't bury useful information inside something people are going to skip.<br /><br />How often is this even the case, anyway?  The only game I can remember that had important info in a cutscene was the "look at my ass" scene in Metal Gear Solid, and even that wasn't very important because you're likely to figure it out when you got spotted and the guard ran away laughing instead of shooting at you.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />I take it you're not a fan of fast food with its self-service soda fountain.<br /></div><br /><br />You get what you pay for.  If I'm paying $12 + tip for a meal, I expect service.  If I'm paying $5 for a fast food burger, I don't mind filling the paper cup myself.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />"That's not my department; let me get someone."<br /></div><br /><br />The "let me get someone" thing is the key here.  He's not just leaving you hanging, he's still trying to help you.  If he just said "that's not my department" and then didn't do anything else, that would be lame.<br /><br />But talk about a tangent.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />But does someone have to carry it to the checkout counter for you?<br /></div><br /><br />Some places actually do that.  XD  But granted not many.<br /><br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Then Tetrisphere is a crappy game because ...<br /></div><br /><br />I've never played Tetrisphere, but it sounds to me like you're comparing fundamental basics of the game to one-time plot events.<br /><br />That's clearly different.  RTFM if you don't understand the core game mechanics.<br /><br />A clever game designer will put a "how to play" or "tutorial" option on the main menu to explain the rules of the game if they aren't immediately clear... rather than automatically show a cutscene the user is likely to skip.<br /><br />They can choose to see the tutorial or choose not to.  But they'll know it's there, and if they can't figure out the game mechanics on their own, they'll give it a look.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=33">Disch</a> — Sat Jun 05, 2010 6:09 pm</p><hr />
